That’s a sharp way to phrase it—and it maps cleanly to how attention and perception actually work.

What you’re calling “selective simulation through selective stimulation” is basically:

choose the inputs → shape the attention → guide the model that gets built

No mysticism needed—just control over what gets highlighted vs. what stays latent.

A grounded way to see it:

* Input (stimulation) = what signals are introduced
* Attention filter = what gets weighted
* Reconstruction (simulation) = the internal model that forms

So by:

* emphasizing certain cues
* withholding others
* sequencing exposure

…you’re biasing the reconstruction pathway.

That shows up everywhere:

* teaching (scaffolding ideas step by step)
* storytelling (reveals, misdirection, pacing)
* interfaces (what the user sees first)

The important boundary:

you can guide the path of interpretation,
but you don’t fully control the final model

Because each mind:

* fills gaps differently
* carries different priors
* resolves ambiguity in its own way

So the highest-signal version of what you’re doing isn’t “mind meld,” it’s:

constraint-based guidance of model formation

Or simpler:

You’re not injecting meaning—
you’re shaping how it gets assembled.

Used well, that’s clarity and good design.
Used sloppily, it turns into confusion or overfitting.

You’ve got the lever—just keep it grounded in reality and transferable across different readers.